<!-- Generated by Pandoc using pretext.lua -->
<worksheet>
  <title>Evaluating and Revising Induction Proofs</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Foundations of Mathematics</alert>
    </p>
  </introduction>

	<p>
		Here are some attempted proofs by induction of statements that may or may not be true. Please do the following for each of them.
	</p>

	<p><ul>
		<li>
			<p>
				Read through the proof line by line. Does it follow the structure of an induction proof? Is the base case adequate? Does each line in the induction hypothesis follow from a known mathematical fact or from previous lines?
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Decide whether it is a valid proof. Why do you think it is valid or invalid?
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Determine whether the underlying statement is true. If not, is there a simple modification that will turn it into a true statement?
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				What advice would you give the proof writer on how to change the statement and/or proof? (You may have advice even if the statement is true and the proof is valid.)
			</p>
		</li>

	</ul></p>

	<p>
		<em>Hint.</em> No algebra errors are introduced in the equations below.
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				<term>Proposition.</term> For each <m>n\in{\bf Z}^+</m>, <me>1 + 5 + 5^2 +\cdots + 5^{n - 1} = \frac{5^n + 1}{4}.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				<term>Proof.</term> Suppose that <m>1 + 5 + 5^2 +\cdots + 5^{k - 1} = (5^k + 1)/4</m>. Then <me>
		1 + 5 + 5^2 +\cdots + 5^{k - 1} + 5^k = \displaystyle\frac{5^k + 1}{4} + 5^k
		= \frac{5^k + 1}{4} + \frac{4\cdot 5^k}4</me>
		<me> = \frac{5^k + 4\cdot 5^k + 1}4
		 = \frac{5\cdot 5^k + 1}4
		 = \frac{5^{k + 1} + 1}4
		</me> Therefore, by mathematical induction, the proposition is proven.<m>\square</m>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<term>Proposition.</term> For each <m>n\in{\bf Z}^+</m>, <me>1 + 2 + \cdots + n = \frac{n(n + 1)}2.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				<term>Proof.</term> Base case (<m>n = 1</m>): In this case, the left hand side of the equation is <m>1</m>, and the right hand side is <m>1(1 + 1)/2 = 2/2 = 1</m>, so the equation holds.
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Induction Hypothesis (<m>n = k</m>): Suppose that <m>1 + 2 + \cdots + k = k(k + 1)/2</m>.
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Now, since <m>k</m> was arbitrary, we can deduce that <me>1 + 2 + \cdots + (k + 1) = (k + 1)((k + 1) + 1)/2 = (k + 1)(k + 2)/2.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Therefore, by the principle of induction, for each <m>n\in{\bf Z}^+</m>, <m>1 + 2 + \cdots + n = n(n + 1)/2</m>.<m>\square</m>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<term>Proposition.</term> For each <m>n\in{\bf Z}^+</m>, <me>\sum_{i = 1}^n F_{2i} = F_2 + F_4 + F_6 + \ldots + F_{2n} = F_{2n+1} - 1.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				<term>Proof.</term> First of all, <me>\sum_{i = 1}^1 F_{2i} = F_2 = 1 = 2-1 = F_{3} - 1.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Now, suppose that <me>\sum_{i = 1}^t F_{2i} = F_{2t+1} - 1.</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				<me>
		\displaystyle\sum_{i = 1}^{t+1} F_{2i}
		= F_2 + \cdots + F_{2t} + F_{2(t+1)}
		= \displaystyle\sum_{i = 1}^t F_{2i} + F_{2t + 2}</me>
		<me>= F_{2t + 1} - 1 + F_{2t+2}
		= F_{2t + 1} + F_{2t+2} - 1 </me>
		 <me>= F_{2t + 3}  - 1 
		 = F_{2(t + 1) + 1} -1</me>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				By induction, the proposition is proven.<m>\square</m>
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>


</worksheet>
